<p>A South Korean court sentenced former President Yoon Suk Yeol to a five-year prison term in the first criminal ruling stemming from his brief 2024 martial law declaration. The conviction addressed allegations tied to how the decree was implemented, with reports describing the case as involving obstruction of justice and the decision-making process around the cabinet during the declaration. The verdict kicks off a wider legal process, with multiple additional trials still ahead, underscoring how South Korea is using courts and formal procedures to resolve a major political rupture.</p><img src='https://kagiproxy.com/img/41MkSVz6qRhQFGBpFBirPrOcpnyNo5jZmpMh2Fhl_BHAt9_29Rfty3czF2PhPm-Gf2tfgeDeOanynhmE8s7AvMGRgTivPbOBI14rSSsOqcHkHvloBzfB2yOOzI3VLlXaqRDcacRS2ik9NhC0lRSXIOTTVxGvmT_sIyf8OmBJAKvdMBpz_bCfRSMFniBwI7dq-ITyTg' alt='A police convoy leaving the residence of former President Yoon Suk Yeol after detaining him in January 2025.' /><br /><h3>Highlights:</h3><ul><li>More cases ahead: The five-year sentence comes in the first of eight trials related to the martial law decree, meaning further court decisions could still reshape the overall legal picture.</li><li>Rebellion charge: An independent counsel has sought the death penalty on an allegation that the martial law enforcement amounted to rebellion, and the court is set to rule on that request on Feb. 19.</li><li>Forgery acquittal: One report says the court acquitted Yoon of a document-forgery allegation while convicting on other counts linked to the 2024 declaration.</li><li>Public mood: Deutsche Welle reports that many South Koreans appear eager to move on from the crisis, framing the ruling as a potential step toward political closure.</li></ul><h3>Perspectives:</h3><ul><li>Seoul court (as reported): The court imposed a prison sentence tied to conduct surrounding the martial law decree, while acquitting Yoon on an alleged document-forgery count. (<a href='https://www.trtworld.com/article/9064201d57ea?utm_source=e059f50d6d80'>TRT World (AFP)</a>)</li><li>Independent counsel (as reported): The independent counsel has asked the court to impose the death sentence on a charge that Yoon’s martial law enforcement amounted to rebellion. (<a href='https://www.pbs.org/newshour/world/a-south-korean-court-sentences-yoon-to-5-years-in-prison-in-first-of-8-trials-related-to-martial-law-decree'>PBS NewsHour</a>)</li><li>South Korean public (as described): Many people want to put the martial law crisis behind them and “turn the page,” according to interviews and analysis in the report. (<a href='https://www.dw.com/en/can-south-korea-turn-the-page-with-yoon-suk-yeol-in-prison/a-75537944'>DW</a>)</li><li>Prosecutors and investigators (as described): The case forms part of broader proceedings, with multiple trials emerging from Yoon’s short-lived martial law move. (<a href='https://www.nytimes.com/2026/01/16/world/asia/south-korea-yoon-prison-martial-law.html'>The New York Times</a>)</li></ul><h3>Sources:</h3><ul><li><a href='https://www.nytimes.com/2026/01/16/world/asia/south-korea-yoon-prison-martial-law.html'>Ex-South Korean Leader Gets Prison Term in First Ruling Over Martial Law</a> - nytimes.com</li><li><a href='https://www.dw.com/en/can-south-korea-turn-the-page-with-yoon-suk-yeol-in-prison/a-75537944'>Can South Korea turn the page with Yoon Suk Yeol in prison?</a> - dw.com</li><li><a href='https://www.pbs.org/newshour/world/a-south-korean-court-sentences-yoon-to-5-years-in-prison-in-first-of-8-trials-related-to-martial-law-decree'>A South Korean court sentences Yoon to 5 years in prison in first of 8 trials related to martial law decree</a> - pbs.org</li><li><a href='https://www.trtworld.com/article/9064201d57ea?utm_source=e059f50d6d80'>A high court in Seoul, South Korea, sentences former president Yoon Suk Yeol to five years in prison for obstructing justice and excluding cabinet members during his 2024 martial law declaration, while acquitting him of document forgery. (AFP via TRT World)</a> - trtworld.com</li></ul>